##### Connection to Hypothesis (Figure 2):
Figure 2 provides information on the number and proportion of civilian harm in the Middle East and Central Asia. As shown in the table, it is evident that the proportion of civilian harm in the Middle East is almost double that of Central Asia. This supports my hypothesis that an increase in U.S. military intervention is associated with higher levels of harm to noncombatants especially given the higher rate of U.S. intervention in the MENA region. The amplified levels of civilian casualties can give rise to radical and extremist movements.


::: {.cell}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-4-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


##### Connection to Hypothesis (Figure 3):
Figure 3 reveals that higher levels of drone strikes are correlated with higher levels of civilian harm. This will provide helpful background to compare the levels of civilian deaths following selective and non-selective attacks. The figure illustrates some periods of correlation, though in 2016 the graph reveals a period of inverse correlation. More research must be done to see whether the drone strikes used in this time frame were selective. If so, this would support my hypothesis. 


::: {.cell}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-5-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


##### Connection to Hypothesis (Figure 4):
Figure 4 in combination with Figure 3 directly supports my hypothesis. Figure 3 shows a spike in civilian harm around 2012 while Figure 4 shows a rise in terrorist attacks in 2015. If the nature of the civilian harm was indiscriminate, then this may have fueled radical activity and the rise of extremist groups, following the period of time after the drone strikes. The increase in attacks suggests that U.S. interventions may not suppress terrorist activity, but inadvertently support it.


::: {.cell}
::: {.cell-output-display}

